            PLANNED PARENTHOOD V CASEY

            	states have been regulating provision of abortion

            		court struck them down

            		the membership of the court changes

            		the court's attitudes toward identical regulations is now different

            		these cases test the court's commitment to roe


            	starts with "Liberty finds no refuge in a jurisprudence of doubt."

            	stare decisis: roe should be upheld

            	the right here is unique

            		it's not the right to have an abortion

            		it's the right to SELF-DEFINITION

            			griswold is not about a right to condoms, it's about a right to marital privacy


            	they affirm that the right to privacy includes the right to have an abortion

            	it's a right for women to self-define according to her own sense of belief and identity

            		this a broad definition of the right

            		right to an abortion would be a narrow defintion (not correct, though)

            the court stands by their duty to protect the right

            they justify their use of heightened review

            	-MANAGABLE: the court asserts that this is all justiciable and administrable

            	-RELIED ON: a generation of women have grown up knowing its available and they rely on it

            		these women know the court is protecting womens right to self definition

            	-STILL RELEVANT: no new legal theory here, roe is not like plessy (invalidated by BROWN) or lochner (invalidated by west coast hotel)

            		the world has not changed like with plessy, and theory has not changed either

            	if the court invalidated roe:

            		things would be terrible!

            		it would negatively impact women who had relied on it

            		it would negatively impact the court if they backpedaled

            			their legitimacy depends on maintaining roe

            			if they back off they look like dorks, like they caved to political pressure

            				they want to feel like a netural arbiter, not like they feel political pressure


            The court upholds Roe, but fundamentally changes it

            	viability was a key measure in Roe

            	viability is still the point where the state can reg about the fetus

            	the trimester scheme is out

            		they say it wasnt a main point in roe

            		though it was...

            		they also think there was something wrong about it

            			it misconceives the interests at stake

            				-WOMENS' HEALTH IS NOT CONFINED TO TRIMESTERS, IT'S A CONTINUOUS CONCERN

            				-trimester scheme undervalues states interest in the fetus too

            				-STATE INTEREST IN FETUS BECOMES COMPELLING AT THE MOMENT OF CONCEPTION

            	THERE IS NO MORE TRIMESTER SCHEME

            	the state interest are compelling throughout the pregnancy

            	but the right to privacy persists

            		it lives along side a wider field for state regulation

            		the entire pregnancy is opened to narrowly tailored regulation

            	Roe's SS standard dies, and with compelling state interests throughout the preg

            	now, the court must look at each regulation throughout the pregnancy

            	the point of viability still matters.  states can prohibit termination of viable fetuses



            STATES NOW CANNOT PLACE AN UNDUE BURDEN

            	STATES CAN REG SO LONG AS IT DOES NOT HAVE THE PURPOSE OR EFFECT TO POSE A SUBSTANTIAL OBSTACLE

            	we're interested in application of the undue burden standard

            	PROVISION OF INFORMATION is not an undue burden

            		woman comes in and wants an abortion, but she has to read a pamphet first

            		not an undue burden

            		provision of information serves the health of the mother, which is a CGP throughout

            		informing them allows women to avoid unforseen psychological consequences

            		just fine so long as its not misleading

            	24 HOUR WAITING PERIOD

            		this is a bigger burden

            		two trips means a higher cost

            		the waiting period serves the interest: health of the mother

            			how does this help?

            				it allows a woman to deliberate and make a better decision

            		this is closer to a substantial obstacle, but it's not there

            		it still informs women, and serves the psychological health of the mother

            		just fine

            	REPORTING REQUIREMENTS

            		also upheld bc they serve the health of the mother

            	NOTIFICATIONS TO HUSBANDS

            		this IS an undue burden because evidence shows women get beat

            		reporting to parents is fine because parents are dominant over kids

            		reporting to husbands is not OK because it subjugates women

            			this is inconsistent with the broader definition of the right

            			it denies their right to self definition


            		this is sort of strange because it's inconsistent with the differential funding

            			the gov didnt make the abusive relationship

            			the logic of these other cases would allow the states to reg this way

            			the court is a little unstable in this respect

            			your self determination is or is not limited by the circumstances



            	differential funding cases: gov placed no obstacle in the path of women, RBR upheld

            	here: state defnitely places an obstacle, but upheld because not substantial

            		two different methods of upholding a law

            		one says right now impacted at all

            		other says right is impacted, sure, but not a substantial obstacle


            	they serve the state interest in the health of the mother and they do not place an undue burden

            	NO MORE SS of abortion laws


            STEVENS DISSENT:

            	provision of information is not really about protecting health

            	because everyone gets it

            	the court is actually giving a free pass to the state

            	the court doesnt ask the hard questions

            		is this really about the health of the mother?

            	this isnt a failure, though, because the court has no obligation to do this outside of HR


            UNDUE BURDEN ANALYSIS LOWERS THE STD OF REVIEW, even as maj gives a broader definition of the right


            ROE KINDA STANDS:


            FUNDAMENTAL RIGHT TO PRIVACY STILL ALLOWS FOR ABORTIONS

            SAME INTERESTS STILL EMPOWER GOV, health of woman, potential life of fetus

            VIABILITY IS STILL SPECIAL, gov can prohibit all abortions at this point



            THING HAVE CHANGED THOUGH:


            whole preg can now be regd

            no more SS, now undue burden

            the state need only show its not doing something with the purpose or effect of placing a substantial obstacle in the way of a woman having an abortion



            CRITICISMS:

            conservatives:

            stare decisis argument isnt even stuck to

            standing on the roe point makes court seem political, not apolitical

            scalia compares it to dred scott

            undue burden doesnt make sense because there's no FR here

            liberals:

            this is a lower standard than SS

            you've given more leeway to the states

            third approach:

            blackmun says EP and FR analysis should play

            even though this is not a FR issue, THEY ARE EP VIOLATIONS

            these laws only affect women

            blackmun says these arent gender neutral reg classifications (who's seeking an abortion)

            	the classification is between the women and men

            	there should be IR

            	if you still had ROE, you wouldnt need IR because roe gave you one better: SS

            	but

            	since we dont have roe, why not bring out the old EP analysis?

            		IR might overturn more laws than undue burden


            these waiting requirements are related to an archaic overbroad attitude about women

            	if thats the case, then you could craig and VMI those bastards

            the court doesn't go in that direction though



            GONZALES v CARHART

            	state partial-birth abortion law struck down because too vague

            	the political definition of the procedure was too broad

            	the effect, but not purpose, was to place a substantial burden

            	the federal law at issue here is not too broad

            		its limited to a specific feature
            		it uses anatomical landmarks
            		there's an intent requirement

            		the court is satisfied it doesnt suffer from same indefiniteness

            the government's interest here is in the potential life of the fetus

            	it does it by restricting certain methods

            	there's still plenty of methods left

            	ginsburg:  this method devalues life in an egregious way

            	disaproving of this allows gov to express its valuation of the life of the fetus

            	gov sends a signal about this method

            the gov also advances its interest in the health of the mother

            	some say this procedure is better for physical reasons (DISPUTED)

            	the state advances psychological health reasons

            		a method is being prohibited in order to prevent women from the psychological burden

            	kennedy and the maj join the gov in showing women how dreadful the procedure is



            to what end are women being informed?

            	to inform decision making

            	but the info can't be misleading

            	here, they're not really offering neutral info

            	it's more like part of a propaganda campaign

            	casey: big decision, need info here it is, wait it out, and come back

            	here:  state should be able to push their info and perspective on the issue

            	as long as they don't distort, they can give just one side


            presenting info from a single point of view is fine

            	it's not a substantial burden



CON LAW DAY 18

    PLANNED PARENTHOOD V CASEY

    	state has an interest from the moment of conception

    	roe trimester schedule is gone

    	the test of these regulations in not SS

    		no compelling means test
    		no narrowly tailored

    	THE TEST IS NOW THE UNDUE BURDEN STANDARD

    		no purpose or effect of placing a SUBSTANTIAL OBSTACLE in the way of an abortion

    		the undue burden std works from conception to viability

    	the WOMAN STILL RETAINS A FUNDAMENTAL RIGHT TO PRIVACY

    		the casey court defines the right as a RIGHT OF SELF DEFINITION

    	VIABILITY is still an important point in the pregnancy

    		even though trimester scheme gone

    		state can prohibit abortion entirely at viability

    		without the undue burden std

    		there have to be exceptions to save the life of the mother

    	the court distinguishes casey from lochner and plessy

    		there, facts and understandings had changed

    		here, facts were the same

    		women had come to rely on the existence of roe

    		the court would lose legitimacy by invalidating roe

    	the state can place obstacles (24h waiting period) but they cannot be substantial

    	the state cannot give husbands veto power over their wives abortions


    GONZALEZ V CARHART

    	congress declared partial-birth abortion to be never medically necessary

    		despite science to the contrary

    	this was a narrowly defined ban

    	they apply the undue burden std

    		you can raise the cost of an abortion in the service of one of the two interests

    		and as long as its not a substantial block

    	here, the ban serves both interest in health of mother and interest in potential life of the fetus

    		there's a loose connection to informing women and helping them protect mental health

    		and it reflects respect for potential life of the fetus

    	there's not a tight connection between means and ends

    		nonetheless its constitutional

    	it's a lower std than SS because interests need not be compelling

    	and also the nexus between means and ends need not be very tight

    		(how is denial of a procedure type beneficial to her health?  it's indirect)

    	court claims this is an advancement of casey

    	they assert that the court is going to be friendly toward abortion ban regulations



