    ZABLOCKI v REDHAIL

    Wisconsin statute requires fathers to pay their child support before they get married

    	EP analysis:  treats groups of grooms differently based on their capacity to pay child support

    		[the court claims to approach this through EP]

    	the amount of money you have is non-suspect

    		amount of money you have is mutable and relevant

    	so this only has to pass RBR, ostensibly

    	they don't do this

    	they find a FR to marriage

    		we know its FR bc there's precedent for it and traditional roots

    		marriage is not two steps away from the listed rights

    			it's right there with the other FR only one step away from the listed ones

    			it's not attached as in hanging on them, but it's part of their family

    	but they don't apply SS

    	they use some intermediate std

    		(sufficiently important state interest and closely tailored)

    			closely tailored < (narrowly tailored == necessary)

    	the fit is not sufficiently close

    		it doesn't get any money to the kids

    		it just prevents that dads from marrying (vertical fit)

    		there are better ways to serve this end (horizontal fit)

    	there are other regs that impinge on the right to marry

    		no incest, no marrying if you have VD

    		these would fly

    		this would not


    	this is like skinner (econ classification, RBR unless FR)

    		they do find a FR, but they apply a middle level of review

    		it leaves intact a lot of other regs of marriage



    	in the abortion funding cases (maher v roe and its neighbor)

    		gov blocked funding for certain types of abortions

    		court did not even apply a heightened level of review

    		its a FR case in roe era, so whould be SS

    		but they don't because it's economic status not gov action

    		the state is not touching a FR at all

    	here, the court says a FR does trigger HR

    		why not just tell the grooms to get a job?

    		it was good enough in abortion cases, but not here

    		in the abortion context, gov places some restriction related to money, no aplgy

    		in this context, the opposite

    		it's plainly inconsistent, which is the court's prerogative

    CONCURRENCES:

    	powell and stewart both opt for the due process clause

    	they say it would have helped the court constrain its decision

    		EP affects the way the gov chooses to regulate

