    BOWERS v HARDWICK

    	Georgia's anti-sodomy statute criminalizes all sodomy

    	the court defines the right at stake here as:

    		the right to same-sex sodomy

    	they go out looking for it

    		they try to find it deeply rooted in tradition (moore, east cleveland)

    		it's not there, even before american law

    	therefore RBR

    	therefore upheld

    	[the narrower you define the right, the less likely you are to find it in tradition]

    		 a broader definition of a right allows you to find it in the past

    	the court here does no EP analysis

    	THIS CASE OVERTURNED BY LAWRENCE v TEXAS


    LAWRENCE v TEXAS

    	TX statute criminalizes same-sex sodomy

    	the court tries to find a fundamental right to PRIVACY

    		they define the right as the right of everyone to privacy in the home
    		and as a right to self-definition (kennedy's casey language)

    		why define this as a right to privacy instead of a right to sodomy?

    			BROADLY DEFINING WHAT RIGHT IS AT STAKE ALLOWS YOU TO STRIKE DOWN THE LAW

    		step one: frame the right as a right to self-definition instead of sodomy

    			it's demeaning to the gays to frame the right so narrowly

    			BOWERS FRAMED THE RIGHT INCORRECTLY

    		step two: abandon the [incorrect] traditional/historical analysis

    			the court points to an evolving set of attitudes and beliefs

    				there's a broad trend across the world and scholarship

    				people treat homosexuality better these days

    			BOWERS ONLY LOOKED AT THE PAST, NOT AT THE TRAJECTORY WE'RE ON

    		The court uses a DP analysis

    		they find a FR and do EP a bit too

    		but they want to prevent the existence of even a well-crafted antisodomy law

    			they want to scrub out the stigma

    			they do it by making a FR to self definition

    			and they seal it up with a DP FR analysis


    		OCONNOR would strike this down under RBR on bare desire to harm

    			but this would leave space for criminalization of all sodomy

    				or well crafted laws that criminalize gay sodomy

    	We found fundamental rights all over this lecture (except bower)

    	SS is not applied here

    		no one knows what's really applied here

    	theres no rational interest, but we don't know why its failed

    		SCALIA freaks the fuck out


    	here, and in the future, we have FR without SS


CON LAW 19

    Last time:

    	we've been moving along a continuum

    		-listed rights
    		-IMPLIED FUNDAMENTAL RIGHTS

    			(P&I was rejected as a source)

    			back in the day substantive due process was identified as a source of FR

    			a heightened test of reaosnableness was used throughout the LOCHNER era

    				they mainly protected economic rights

    			The court constrained the state's regulatory authority

    			BLAISDELL ended the LOCHNER era

    				they expanded the regulatory power of the state

    				to do so, they eliminated the freedom to contract as a fundamental right

    			skinner gave the start of the intersection of DPFR and EP analyses

    		HOW DOES COURT ID A FR?

    		HOW DOES COURT USE DP AND EP TO ANALYSZE A CASE?


    		there is a right to family that is

    			DEEPLY ROOTED IN OUR TRADITION and HISTORY

    			(goldberg's concurrence in griswold)

    			FR to family also can be found because of CONSEQUENCES

    			also can be found in the PENUMBRA / periphery of enumerated rights

    		why no SS for every FR?

    			maybe they were worried about calling other laws into Q


    	ZABLOCKI

    		FR to marry

    		no SS, HR instead

    		struck down on fit grounds

    		they to the analysis under EP here

    			why not DPFR?
    			why not SS?

    		they're worried about too sweeping a ruling

    			"we are not a superlegislature, we are not a lochner court"

    		ability to pay was a condition for exercising the right to marry

    			san antonio v rodriguez: ability to pay did not matter bc no FR to EDU

    			in the abortion funding cases, the FR to privacy gave us a FR

    				but still not a big deal because the limitations did not touch right to privacy

    					gov's policy has nothing to do with right to privacy, says court

    					it's your own doing, not the gov's


    	BOWERS

    		They identify a narrowly defined right (right to gay sex)

    			law was about all sodomy, but the case was about gay sodomy

    		they try to use the "deeply rooted" method

    		but that's a way to blow off the case



    	LAWRENCE

    		The court shifts the definition of the right we're looking for

    			they dont ask the bower q

    			they ask, is there a liberty of self definition that includes defining yourself through you itnimate relatinoships

    		the court looks to history again

    			GOLDBERG: DEEPLY ROOTED

    			HARLAN: TRADITION AS A TRAJECTORY

    			nonprocreative sex has been prohibited

    			but attitudes have been changing

    			we're headed towards more liberty of self definition as far as intimate behavior

    			they don't say whether the right is fundamental

    				we might say it's fundamental based on the casey definition of self definition

    		THE COURT DOES NOT SAY: this is a FR

    		Oconnor looks at it as an EP RBR failure


    		Sexual orientation laws:

    			oconnor says RBR

    			MAJ gives no answer


    		we don't get a statement that this liberty is fundamental
    		we don't get the level of review IDd
    		we don't see any ruling about the kind of classification sexual orientation is
    		we dont see analogies to other rights


    		we are told that the proper framing of the right is the liberty of self definition

    			find this for same sex couples in TRAJECTORY, not strictly in the past


    		The court is trying to give a very limited ruling

    			they only care about criminalization of gay sodomy

    			they don't want to call all sexual orientation laws into question


    			dissent:  MAJ not being humble, they just want freedom



    TODAY:


    we're finishing the story of implied FR and EP


    WASHINGTON v GLUCKSBERG

    	statute criminalizes assistance of suicide

    	the issue: is there a FR at stake?

    		if yes, WA must defend their law
    		if no, conversation over

    	IS THERE A FR TO ASSISTED SUICIDE?

    		(this is a concrete specific framing of the right)

    		they do it this way because of a fear of lochner

    	They see a long history of the opposite of a right to assisted suicide

    		THERE IS NO RIGHT TO ASSISTED SUICIDE IN OUR HISTORY

    	no FR, so RBR:

    		the state IDs a lot of state interests at stake

    			theyre all legit or compelling

    		the means are rationally related


    	BUT there's other methods of IDing FR

    		souter uses the trends arguments

    		personal autonomy is at stake (casey)


    	BREYER:  there's this issue of extreme suffering

    		we could make a consequentialist argument about pain

    		if WA had outlawed palliative care, then this would play different

    		this bit suggests there might be something fundamental here


    	GLUCKSBERG stands for:  look to history for FR, define the right at the most specific level (1997)

    		CASEY:  right at stake is self definition / autonomy (1992)

    		glucksberg backs off the casey "general right to personal autonomy"

    		the precedential value of a broad framing does not carry

    		ADDS SOME STUFF, but nothing terribly new

    			we already knew how to look to deeply rooted traditions

    			its new in that it insists in narrow definitions of rights (right to assisted suicide)

    			in this respect, it jives with bowers

    			it also tells us each FR claim must have its own justification

    				this is because of a fear of lochner

    				this methodolgy limits the court's power and discretion

    				this restrains the court from inventing new rights

    					this method happens to reject most claims of rights

    					it wants concrete practices from the past for its justifications



    UNITED STATES v WINDSOR

    	2013

    	it's about DOMA (federal defense of marriage act)

    	the court asserts that right to regulate marriage rests with the state

    	the feds came down on a gay couple tax-wise

    	there's a federalism concern that the congress is edging in on state turf

    		it does not get invalidated on federalism grounds, though


    	KENNEDY strikes this law down on BARE DESIRE TO HARM

    		think Moreno, Romer

    		thats an EP analysis

    		they claim theres NO GOV purpose beyond the purpose of burdening the group

    		the disparate burden does not make it unconstitutional on its own (BARE DESIRE)

    			but a lack of other purposes added on does

    			its not about the burden, its about the lack of legit justifications

    			hatred of hippies is not alone enough

    				you don't need muchm it's RBR, but there's gotta be something

    		Romer analogy:

    			we have here sweeping, durable disabilities imposed by DOMA

    			feds are going way beyond the usual scope

    			its unusual in its sweep

    			there's no precedent for taking a subset of marriages and giving them a disability

    		Starts out looking like a federalism issue, but that's a fak out

    		instead, it's about this unusual sweeping law that targets a set of marriages without justification


    		THERE'S NO FR IDd HERE

    		THERE'S NO INDICATION OF SUSPECT/QS/NS CLASSIFICATION

    	this case isnt really an EP analysis

    		we jump straight from the facts of the case into bare desire to harm

    		we do none of the steps

    		we don't know what classification we're dealing with

    	the court says its not about same sex marriage, but instead about bare desire to harm

    	SCALIA:  don't beleive it!  I told you not to beleive it!

    		it's really all about same sex marriage!

    		he wants the leg to do its job, and the court to do its job



    	THIS CASE FLOATS AROUND OUR DOCTRINAL TOOLS

    		but it does not move through our flow chart

    		some stuff is missing

    			no analysis of what classification

    			we go straight to fails RBR

    		marriage is a FR, but they don't do a FR analysis

    		BY NOT SAYING THESE THINGS, THE COURT CONSTRAINS ITS DECISION

    			(fear of lochner)

    		the dissenters say this fuzziness is about being political


    OBERGEFELL v HODGES

    	Prohibition on same sex marriage

    	1- is there a right to same sex marriage?
    	2- are states required to recognize same sex marriages from other states

    		if 1 is yes, 2 is yes also
    		q2 is kind of an insurance policy
    		q2 would not be a rights analysis, itd be about relationships between states
    		q2 does come up because:

    	THERE IS A RIGHT TO SAME SEX MARRIAGE

    	THERE IS A RIGHT TO SELF-DEFINITION and AUTONOMY

    		this is a bit like casey, lawrence

    		this is not like glucksberg

    			it frames a broad liberty

    	is this right fundamental?

    		casey would say yes

    		others would say no

    		the court sets aside glucksberg

    			which turns down the rule that each reqs its own justification

    	they also don't commit to history the way glucksberg did

    	PROTO-CONSEQUENTIALIST ARG:

    		without this right, families and children are negatively impacted

    		without this right, individuals suffer in terms of their family lives

    		these consequences together suggest a FR

    			but the court does not carry out this argument

    	ANALOGY between same-sex couples who are married and opposite sex couples who are married

    		MARRIAGE IS a FR for opposite sex couples

    		lots of cases recognize this

    		all the same reasons for making marriage a FR count for gays too

    		-it creates a stable environment for children
    		-its about self definition
    		-enduring compainship
    		-keystone of social order

    		same sex couples are the same as opposite sex couples in these respects

    	PROTO-TRADITION ARGUMENT

    		there's a trajectory toward giving rights to gay couples


    	If there's a FR here, we would expect SS (or maybe HR)

    		there's no SS analysis here

    			the court spends almost no time investigating the reasons behind these bands

    			doctrinally, we would expect to see this

    			they don't do a fit analysis

    			they dont talk about what kind of classification

    			they don't tell us what level of review

    			it leaves a lot of Qs open like lawrence


    	The dissent accuses the MAJ of characterizing those opposed to same sex marriage as animated by hatred

    		they say they're not bigots who oppose same sex marriage


    	The court is not measuring the state justification against some doctrinal test

    	They say that individuals can hold views opposite without being bad, but turning it into public policy demeans the people in same sex marriages

    	why leave so many questions open?

    		it restrains the decision somehwat



    	DISSENTS:

    		Slippery slope to polygamy

    		Slippery slope to tyrrany

    		Scalia attacks the unrepresentative qualoities of the court

    		the court corrupts our doctrinal framework



    	The court is still not up to establishing a fundamental right to autonomy

    	OBERGEFELL demonstrates to us the flexibility of the doctrine


CON LAW DAYS 20 & 21


    We wrapped up implied fundamental rights

    IDing them is the tough part, ostensibly

    Lochner fears make this extra tricky

    when they find one, they're supposed to use SS, but they don't


    WASH v GLUCKBERG

    	added to our IDing toolkit

    	part of their method was familiar

    		"deeply rooted in tradition"

    		bowers, etc

    	new in gluck:

    		-the right must be narrowly framed and specifically described
    			(not "right to autonomy" rather "right to assisted suicide")
    			this is supposed to restrain judicial decisions
    			it prevents lochnerish overreach

    		-each claim of a fundamental right must be justified on its own
    			eg in casey the right to self definition does not extent to suicide

    		-narrows greatly the number of rights we're likely to find out there


    US v WINDSOR and OBERGEFELL v HODGES

    	case decides without deciding
    	they answer an issue but leave a lot open

    WINDSOR

    	this is an EP analysis

    	law is so sweeping and severe that court can ID a bare desire to harm

    	this is a federal analogue to romer

    	the court did not

    		tell us whether suspect, qs, or ns

    		tell us whether there's a FR
    			it doesnt do any of these:
    			consequences
    			text
    			tradition
    			evolution
    			analogies to prior cases

    OBERGEFELL

    	right to marry comes from precedent

    	do same sex couples have a FR to marry?

    	court proceeded BY ANALOGY

    	the court finds same sex couples similar to opposite sex couples

    	the court defines the right as "right to self definition"

    		contrary to glucksberg's precedent

    		ct:  new right, new rules

    	ct looks to TREND/EVOLUTION
    		we're being nicer to these people

    	ct looks to CONSEQUENCES
    		the children!

    	some of this is familiar, but not locked onto our framework

    	ct does not:

    		ID a level of review
    		application of a level of review
    			(they dont ask what purpose or check fit of means)
    		tell whether suspect, qs, or ns

    	dissent: this is politicians in robes, theyre not acting like a court

    		theyre just voting their values

    		no longer constitutional interp

    	court tries to limit the range of its ruling

    		it leaves things open, to protect itself from unanticipated consequences of a broad ruling

    	maybe this is a new kind of approach, a new doctrine different from our stds

    		Kennedy is leading the way to a new set of tests, perhaps

    		Kennedy is concerned about dignity of individuals and states




