    FREEDOM OF EXPRESSION

    	"Congress shall make no law abridging the freedom of speech, of of the press..."

    	governments have long been concerned with free speech as a destabilizing factor

    		the history of free speech is from the gov's perspective
    		it's a history of abridging free speech

    	Free speech theories:

    		-necessary to find truth
    		-allows us to operate our governments (elections)
    		-necessary to development of the self
    		-keeps governmental power in check
    		-teaches tolerance of differnt points of view
    		-allows development of moral character

    		none of these is in the constitution, but theyre supported in different places

    		some of these theories suggest different scopes for free speech

    			election speech is narrow, self development speech is broad


    SHAFFER

    	1919 birth of modern free speech jurisprudence

    	it's an example of a bad tendency test


    SCHENK v US

    	espionage act

    	some rascals sent out flyers insisting that people resist the draft

    	there's talk of effect of this speech, but no proof or evidence

    	this is called the BAD TENDENCY TEST

    		it looks at effect

    		purpose and effect are bound together

    			no evidence of intent beyond natural and probable consequences

    		this approach doesn't look beyond the document in question

    		ABSTRACT REASONING ABOUT EFFECT AND PURPOSE, NARROWLY FOCUSED ON THE SPEECH ITSELF

    		no exploration of empirical proof

    		its all about the judge's instinct and reasoning about what was said

    			you can constructively infer intent from the publication

    		YOU put the pamphet in front of the judge and let him make a call

    		requires a determination of effect and purpose based on text

    		IF THE EFFECT IS THERE, INTENT IS PRESUMED

    	this case also puts forward a new idea

    	THE CLEAR AND PRESENT DANGER TEST

    		speech would protected unless there's a clear and present danger

    		that some evil would come about that congress seeks to prevent

    		CIRCUMSTANCE, CONTEXT, PROXIMITY, AND DEGREE ALL MATTER HERE

    			this is different from bad consequence test bc it looks to the world beyond the text

    			it asks judge to sift through the context and likely consequences

    		You can shout fire at home, but you cannot shout fire in a theatre

    			you can shout fire if it's a play about fire and its your line
    			you can shout fire if there's really a fire
    			you cannot shout fire if it's not true and you just hope to see a stampede

    		HOW MUCH PROTECTION YOUR SPEECH GETS DEPENDS ON CONTEXT

    		THIS TEST DOES NOT REQUIRE US TO WAIT FOR ACTUAL BAD CONSEQUENCES

    			the gov can criminalize prophylactically

    		it's different from the bad tendency test, but the court still uphold this conviction

    		the time and place of the speech are determinative

    			it's wartime!


    		instead of just looking at the speech, you now look at the time and context

    			both tests allow the gov to send you to prison for what you say

    			but they respond to two different sets of conditions

    			can lead to two different results, but it does not here



    FROHWERK v US

    	german language newspaper, fro was sentenced to prisonfor breeding disloyalty

    	holmes writes for the court

    		he infers probable intent from the likely consequences

    	this is another BAD TENDENCY TEST

    		they say that you don't even have to see any evidence of an effect

    		just the risk of danger is enough

    		they look at the text, and imagine a disruptive consequence

    			this vision allows them to infer intent

    			the sum effect is that this poor bastard is going to jail



    DEBS v US

    	leader of socialist party convicted under espionage act

    	holmes upholds

    	part of the purpose and effect of the speech was to oppose the war

    		most of the speech was about socialism

    		but the court picked out pieces that had a reaosnable tendency to obstruct

    		purpose is inferred from the judicial analysis of the speech

    	if the reasonable consequence of any element of your speech allows a judge to infer intent

    		youre fucked



    THIS IS CONSISTENT WITH THE DEEP HISTORY OF FREE SPEECH

    	there's major restrictions on freedom of speech

    	the judges can send off a punk to jail based on inferences

    THE CLEAR AND PRESENT DANGER TEST

    	allows the judge to look to the context of the speech

    	you check if there's a real possibility of bad consequences

    	not just a tendency within the text, given the right context, to cause bad consequences

    	starting with Abrams, the clear and present danger test moves up from dissents and into cases



    ABRAMS v US

    	russian immigrants convicted for anti-imperialism speech

    	court upholds under not BT

    		if it was BT:
    			the natural consequence is general strike
    			the intent to cause one is apparent
    			we don't have to sweat the actual likely consequences

    	HOLMES' dissent is famous here

    		he changes his mind about free speech over a summer bc of his friends
    		the law stays the same, HOLMES changes

    		he says there's not sufficient intent

    			he now requires specific intent

    			not just intent to cause some action

    				these russian intend to influence US policy toward russia
    				we're not at war with russia, we're at war with germany

    			he now wants to see precise proof of what they actually intended

    			this would be more speech protective

    				it makes it tougher to ID the requisitie element of intent

    				you still focus on the document

    				but you require judges to explain why their inference of intent is justified

    		this vision keeps the BT test but makes it more protective by raising the bar for reaonsableness

    		the point is to protect legitimate criticism of the government

    			we don't want to short circuit debates on policy

    			patriots make good faith arguments that sometimes can hurt the country

    		CLEAR AND PRESENT DANGER TEST

    			looks to consequences

    			does the speech bring about a clear and present danger of evils congress hates?

    			this would let them off the hook, in contrast to BT

    			we shouldn't punish people just for what they believe

    			even if you could infer intent to disrupt, they still shouldnt be punished

    				disagreement is not the beginning of defeat
    				it's a prerequisite for finding the truth

    			There's no clear and present danger given the context

    				therefore all that's getting punished is the view that the russian revolution was OK

    			HOLMES still thinks you can put people in jail for speech

    			but now he thinks we should have a default position of liberty

    				free speech should be the default
    				because the marketplace of ideas allows us to fin the truth


    		APPLICATION of CPD:

    			even if you find intent, there's no clear and presnt danger here

    			"it's a silly leaflet by an unkown man which has no chance of hindering the gov"

    				"puny anonymities"

    				who cares about these pathetic dorks?

    			THERE'S NO CHANCE THEY'VE ACTUALLY CREATED SOMETHING DANGEROUS

    			is he saying you can say anything you want as long as no one cares?


    		HOLMES takes a few positions:

    			if we stay with BT, we should raise the bar

    				we need to make it harder for gov to criminalize free speech

    			we should switch to CPD, though


    		How close is the metaphor of free speech to the marketplace?

    		Is free speech really about truth?

    			holmes says it is


    	We'll continue this trend away from BT after the break



    BREAK


    AN HOUR AGO:

    Freedom of Speech

    	-history of suppression
    	-theories of why free speech is good
    		none is embedded in const
    	-we started with the WWI treatment of free speech

    SCHENCK

    	bad tendency test
    	natural consequence and effect

    	is there any conceivable effect of this speech that could be damaging?

    	if yes, we can infer intent

    		once intent and and effect are established, guilty

    	prohibition on speech was still allowed

    		hurting the draft is like shouting fire


    	CLEAR AND PRESENT DANGER TEST

    		are words used in circumstances and of such a nature that they create a clear and presrnt danger of an evil that congress hates?

    		this focuses on the words, but also the context of the words


    FROHWERK AND DEBS

    	look at the utterance

    	is there a natural harmful effect

    		if yes, intent inferred

    	conviction upheld

    	in debs the bad effects were from one small component of a big speech


    ABRAMS

    	the maj justified bad tendency

    	it's easy to uphold convictions under BT

    	HOLMES:

    		took a new tack

    		he demanded specific proof of intent to cause bad effects

    		even if intent could be found, holmes wanted a different approach

    		he now wants freedom

    		he suggest use of the CPD test that arrives at DIFFERENT RESULTS than BT

    			this distinguishes holmes' attitudes from here from in SCHENCK

    			this would result in different outcomes

    		he know wants a MARKETPLACE OF IDEAS for the purpose of arriving at truth

    			so long as no CPD, let them talk

    			free exchange of ideas produces the most truthful outcomes

    		we should allow free debate because abrams is a puny anonymity

    			they pose NO REAL THREAT

    		holmes forecasts the future here

    		Four questions stay open:

    			how does holmes know this is the const's theory?
    			what roles does triviality play?
    				is speech less protected if it's more potent?
    			how meaningful is the marketplace metaphor?
    				why not regulate this marketplace like all the others?
    			is truth the only point of free expression?
    				self development, eg



    MOVING FORWARD:

    	from modern history to recent history

    	gov can still criminalize free expression even today

    		how hard should it be, though?

    		just like with EP, good reasons can justify infringements, says ct



    GITLOW v NEW YORK

    	state level red scare laws are at issue

    	when can gov supress free expression?
    	how will courts review?
    		with bad tendency test
    		or with CPD test

    	gitlow indicted for anarchism.  member of a left wing socialist group.

    		they created a manifesto that advocated overthrow of gov by force
    		gitlow violates the terms
    		the education and discussion of the idea is permitted under the statute
    		advocacy is forbidden


    	the state can act to protect itself under the police power (constitutional on face)

    	how do we know that gitlow advocated overthrow?

    		we don't, and dont need to

    		all we need to know:
    			do the words imply a tendency to action?
    				this is a bit like BT

    		we don't look to circumstance or context

    			we just look at the criteria in the law

    			so its more restrained than BT
    			it's deference to state leg

    				they made a list of shit that coutns as advocacy
    				ct defers to that

    			it's like BT
    				bc it results in convictions
    				deferential to state
    				easy to supress speech
    				no need to see if anyone acted on the speech
    				it's advocacy if it matches the criteria in the statute
    				default mode is gov suppression of speech
    				no attention to concrete circumstances or consequences

    	HOLMES:

    		goes back to CPD test

    		reasons why there should be no punishment here:

    			-this is just theory
    				we should be allowed to debate it! marketplace of ideas.
    				let the debate go! let the stupid idea fail.
    				this free competition of ideas bit is like abrams

    			--no chance of imminent uprising
    				the danger must be present as in imminent
    				this is someday talk
    				and unlikely to get up to speed anyhow
    				this is all a bit ridiculous



    WHITNEY v CALIFORNIA

    	whitney attends a convention to form a communist party
    	CA criminal syndicalism act prohibits it
    	her defense is that she only wanted moderate politics
    	but the statute criminalizes any participation in the party

    	ct maj uphold conviction

    		not by her intentions
    		rather by the letter of the statute
    			she was a knowing member of this org that advocates criminal behavior
    		she matches the statute, she's convicted, upheld

    	this is about collective activity

    		she's punished for her memberhsip in an organization

    		her specific ideas don't matter

    		because joint action is more problematic than isolated individual speech


    	BRANDEIS dissent (actually turned out a concurrence)

    		clear and present danger test

    		the speech has to pose an actual and imminent serious problem

    			irrational fears and paranoia aren't good enough

    			advocacy does not equate to imminence

    		we need a high threshold on the gov's ability to criminalize speech

    			if you prevent them from criminalizing this type of speech

    			you let time pass

    			the debate plays out, and the idea lives or dies on its merits

    			answer the speech with more speech

    				the solution to dangerous speech is more speech

    				expression should be met with expression not supression

    		this is different from holmes in terms of the benefits of more speech

    			[holmes sees the benefit of more free speech as truth]

    			-he admits we might get more truth
    			-he claims we might also get self-development
    				he asserts that this is the end of all gov
    			-he claims speech can be a stabilizing force on gov
    				silencing dissenters destabilizes gov by bottling tension
    				this is contrary to the deep history of FS
    			-helps with self governance

    		he's almost saying, maybe we should never supress speech
    			bottling that shit up can make ya crazy

    		this vision of free speech claims to align free speech with order
    			by limiting resentment
    			by leading us to self development
    			diversity of points of view/ market

    		He's continuing along the path that Holmes started

    		He adds reasons to the usual argument
    			-self dev
    			-self gov
    			-stabilizes by allowing venting

    	Speech suppression in times of crisis was common
    	Cases work their way up, and they all get upheld

    	In the middle of the 20th c, the swing changes



    DENNIS v US

    	Dennis indicted under smith act
    	he attempted to organize a communist party
    	he conspired to teach overthrow of US gov
    		he's not actually doing anyhting
    		but he's gathering people up
    		to chat about overthrow

    	Court decides not to use Whitney bc too deferential

    	They decide on CPD instead

    		they adopt the Learned Hand formulation:

    		gravity of the evil discounted by improbability of success

    			we're still looking to consequences (different from BT)
    			probability is from the CPD test
    			but it also allows the gov to criminalize way unlikely shit
    				so long as it's horribly evil to the gov
    				even a long shot can be prohibited if its dangerous
    			gov can move proactively if there's a grave evil at stake

    		Everyone agrees that communism is a serious evil

    			Brandeis requires serious harm in order to restrain suprression
    			here, seriousness empowers gov to supress

    	This all is almost like a step back to BT
    		it purports to distance itself from the deferntial old days
    		but it alters the CPD test
    		now it upholds criminalization of free speech
    	Frankfurter would have cited whitney

    	BLACK and DOUGLAS dissent


    BRANDENBURG v OHIO

    	KKK rally

    	court claims to repudiate Whitney

    	they assert the CPD test with teeth

    	TEST:

    		GOV can criminalize speech if there's advocacy that incites imminent lawless action
    		AND it is actually likely to produce that bad action

    		it's no longer enough to try to get someone to beleive something
    		you have to:
    			incite someone
    			to act now
    			and
    			your incitement is likely to work

    		This version of CPD is more like what Holmes and BRandeis talked about

    		it draws the line between idea and action

    	BRANDEBURG is a validation of the history of dissents

    	We'd expect brandenburg to robustly protect speech

    		if gov wants to abridge FS, they must satisfy SS

    		OR

    		it must satisfy the brandenburg test


    HOLDER v Humanitarian law project

    	the brandenburg test would protect the folks here
    	so, go to SS

    	point is national security
    	means = suppression
    		there's a better way to do this

    	Fails

    	this all happens in the dissent, though

    	MAJ:

    		coordination of any sort with terrorists is dangerous

    		if you free up resources here, they can devote that dough to terrorism

    		congress decided that there's to be no touching of terrorists

    			no matter the intention

    		this sounds a bit like whitney

    			both cases involve moderate folks trying to reign in some nutjobs

    		we get here a deferential test again that allows supression of speech

    			maybe holmes was right, and we only get free speech when it doesnt matter
    			as soon as theres conflict or danger, no more freedom


CON LAW DAY 22

    ... (missed some review to sign up for classes)

    We started free speech last time

    	Brandeis' dissent in Whitney continued the latterday Holmes approach


    Up until dennis, panic is grounds to suppress free speech


    DENNIS: clear and present danger test.  but it's the HAND FORMULA:

    	GRAVITY OF EVIL DISCOUNTED BY THE PROBABILITY OF SUCCESS


    BRANDENBURG TEST:

    	Great limit to what speech gov can prohibit:

    	Incitement to violence can be prohibited if you're inciting imminent lawless action that is actually likely to produce that action.

    	there must be a close link between speech and action

    	idle chatter about overthrow of the gov by force is not enough

    	if you fall outside, the gov can still reg

    	it must satisfy SS though


    Humanitarian law project:

    	Breyer says helping terrorists learn law is protected.

    	Breyer says they dont pass SS.  CGP, but not narrowly tailored

    	Breyer shows us how it should work.

    	Maj does an end run around.

    		any assistance you give them frees up resources for terrorism

    		congress has already done the balancing for us

    	even though this is after brandenburg, the court falls back on dennis and whitney and gitlow

    		the maj looks at what the statute says.

    		deferential

    		just because we have brandenburg doesn't mean we always have to use it

    		during times of crisis, the court will defer to legislature on free speech


    The overall trend of the 20th century is a trend toward protecting speech.

    	its not a guarantee though

    	smaller and smaller set of speech that can be criminalized

    	pattern of deference, though too


    These two days were all about dangerous speech





    Today is about FALSE STATEMENTS OF FACT

    	we'll see how and why the court protects them



    NEW YORK TIMES v SULLIVAN

    	famous case, 1964 (like brandenburg)

    	maj of the court wants speech-protective doctrinal tests

    	ALABAMA hick sues NYT for publishing allegedly libelous material


    	OFFICIAL IN HIS OFFICIAL CAPACITY

    		low bar to prove libel, brutal penalty


    	KEY BACKGROUND PRINCIPLE:

    		"DEBATE ON PUBLIC ISSUES SHOULD BE UNINHIBITED, ROBUST, AND WIDE-OPEN"

    		robust debate needs BREATHING SPACE

    		we can't pick out the lies and punish them

    		it would cause a CHILLING EFFECT


    	The pairing of a desire for ROBUST DEBATE and the understanding of CHILLING EFFECT

    		together they frame the case's approach


    	is there a difference between falsehood generally and defamation specifically?

    		not really

    		judges should have thick skin, and public officials too

    		the solution is not to allow the libel suits

    		the solution is for public people to nut up

    		criticism of public life is desirable


    	it does not matter if there's actual damage to a person's reputation

    		the damage to the quality of the debate is greater than the damage to the individual


    	THE TEST FOR DEFAMATION:

    		ACTUAL MALICE


    		this is more than just negligence

    		knowledge or reckless disregard is essential

    		under this test, NYT passes this test

    			they lacked the malice


    	THE COURT identifies a narrow window of speech that can be suppressed

    		they put the burden on the plaintiff to prove defamation

    		actual malice is a tough standard

    		Black (as in brandenburg): this is not enough


    	Public officials have a solution when they're libeled

    		MORE SPEECH

    		we need to let the market of ideas sort this out

    			(except where there's a pressing urgency)

    		the actual malice std is difficult to meet

    		mostly all public officials can do is respond with counter speech


    	SULLIVAN was about a public official engaged in official conduct

    		who is a public official, though?



    CURTIS v BUTTS and AP v WALKER

    	butts was an athletic director
    	brought action for libel
    	after an article accused him of game fixing
    	Walker led a march against civil rights protesters

    	neither is a pure public official

    	if they were public officials, they'd have to meet the Sullivan test

    		they do have to meet that std

    	they're public figures even if theyre not public officials

    		both categories enjoy public influence

    		they've put themselves forward as deciders

    		functionally they occupy similar roles

    	they have the means to speak against the libelous speech

    		they control enough of the debate to make their own remedy


    	This is a larger group, it includes many celebrities


    	same principles from sullivan:

    		open debate
    		no chilling

    	libel suits in these cases would result in too much SELF CENSORSHIP

    	treating public people this way serves the public debate

    	false statements themselves are not valuable
    	effective criticism and good self governance are the goal
    	false statements are the cost of doing business

    	HOW ABOUT PRIVATE INDIVIDUALS?


    GERTZ v ROBERT WELCH, INC

    	a cop (not gertz) shot a kid
    	someone published some article
    	Gertz sues and wins
    	did he meet the right standard?

    	if he's a public official, he's gotta prove actual malice
    	if he's a private individual, its some other std


    	the court does not require actual malice

    	the balance of interests here plays out in favor of protecting private people

    	the state has a greater interest in protecting the reps of private individuals

    		everyone has dignity the gov can and should protect

    		-private people don't has as much power to fight back with more speech

    		-public figures give some of it up by becoming public

    			private people don't volunteer up any of their interest in rep in exchange for power

    			there's an element of consent at play


    	gertz is not a public figure

    		he didn't volunteer himself up

    		he doesn't have power to speak back


    	The first amendment only needs to protect PUBLIC DEBATES

    		not every single argument between individuals


    	The court tries to strike a balance

    		SULLIVAN: public official in public capacity
    		BUTTS: private individual in public capacity
    		GERTZ: private individual in private capacity

    			the state interest in dignity is always there

    			it just counts for a lot less when talking about public people

    			in the discussion about private individuals, the public concerns disappear

    			and

    			the interest in dignity grows

    			THE LESS PUBLIC THE CONFLICT, THE LESS PROTECTED THE SPEECH

    			If the public debate is not at stake, the gov is empowered to act
    				to protect the state interest in individual dignity



    	What if we don't have a public issue?


    DUN & BRADSTREET v GREENMOSS BUILDERS

    	contractor is falsely reported as being bankrupt
    	five subscribers get this news
    	private individual at play

    	we're in the Gertz world, at best

    	the court goes further

    		the issue in question is not a public issue

    	it's a private issue involving private parties

    	The std for proving libel is not actual malice as in sullivan

    		it's much lower


    	NYT builds a framework

    		these other cases flesh out the limits



    US v ALVAREZ

    	congress enacts "stolen valor act"
    	prohibits claiming you won a military medal
    	these facts are not about libel
    	Alvarez is talking about himself

    	can false statements of fact be punished?

    	Greenmoss tells us that it can be easy

    		but this is different

    	there's a public concern

    		but he's telling lies about himself

    	CAN the gov punish a public figure for lying about his own record?

    		this doesnt fit with the ones before it

    	Kennedy:

    		Applies SS

    		this is problematic because it is so broad

    		it punishes a whole broad category of speech

    		it doesn't matter whether you're in public or private,
    		you can't lie about medals under this law

    	So we're not in one of the categories the gov can readily regulate

    		therefore the std should be pretty high

    	Fit:

    		Horizontal and Vertical

    		Vertical: means must actually serve the goal

    		Horizontal fit is a problem here

    			there are ways the gov could protect the meaning of medals
    			WITHOUT suppressing free speech

    			the gov could also just do nothing and let the public expose alvarez

    			the gov could publish database of MoH winners
    				it would facilitate counterspeech


    	BREYER:

    		also thinks it should fail, even under IS

    		it's a FR, you wanna reach for SS

    		but we got False statements of Fact

    			not the most important speech

    		therefore IS, but still this fails

    		This sliding scale approach is like marshall in san antone v rodriguez
    			or like plier v doe


    	ALITO:

    		he would uphold this under RBR
    		there's no chilling here
    		it prevents harm to military
    		there's no debate at stake


    TEST CHANGE
    Another test change

    law-notes/con-law



CON LAW DAY 23


    NYT v SULLIVAN

    	a PUBLIC OFFICIAL IN HIS OFFICIAL CONDUCT must prove ACTUAL MALICE for libel

    		knowingly false or reckless disregard for falsehood

    		hard to meet

    		VERY PROTECTIVE OF CRITICS

    	The court wants a wide-open, ROBUST PUBLIC DEBATE in order to advance good self government

    		lies, falsehoods, and vitriol is all included

    		No holds barred

    	The court should not excise false statements from the debate

    		they have no intrinsic value

    		but they should be protected because

    		CHILLING EFFECT

    	High std of proof burden put on public officials

    		so that we can have a nice solid debate


    CURTIS BUTTS WALKER

    	public figures seem like public officials

    		theyre both involved in public matters

    		and they affect the disposition

    		they're advantageously positioned relative to the mass media

    	therefore they get the same std:  actual malice


    GERTZ

    	private individuals should not have to meet the actual malice std

    		the state has an interest in the preservation of individual dignity

    			but here, private individuals have not offered themselves up to the public

    			they also have less capability to protect themselves in mass media

    		the court sees them as more deserving of protection

    	but it can't be ludicrously easy

    		no presumed damages
    		no punitive damages

    	there's a balance between private individuals's dignity and free speech

    		dignity wins here, opposite of sullivan



    DUN and BRADSTREET v GREENMOSS

    	private people

    	where there's no public issue involved,

    		no worry about chilling

    		digniity interest remains

    	therefore states can have punitive and presumed damages along with a pltf-favorable std



    	THE FURTHER WE GET FROM A PUBLIC DEBATE, THE LESS PROTECTED THE SPEECH

    		sliding scale



    ALVAREZ

    	how does the court know if it's dealing with a public debate issue or not?

    		plurality (KENNEDY):  gov tries to intervene in a first amendment debate

    			it's not libel about an individual

    			it would give the gov a power to police for truth anywhere in public

    			this is an abridgement

    			they apply SS

    			it fails

    		ALITO:

    			he sees this as like greenmoss

    			false statements of fact

    			no consitutional value

    			NO CHILLING EFFECT

    			no self censorship

    			he applies RBR

    		BREYER:

    			tries goldilocks approach

    			false statements can be of value in a public debate

    			but not as valuable as the true statements

    			therefore we should apply IR




    1. FIRST AMENDMENT IS A FR

    	gov must show compelling interest and narrowly tailored

    	that means subject to SS

    2. THE COURT HAS ID'D CERTAIN KINDS OF EXPRESSION THE GOV cAN MORE EASILY REGULATE

    	-clear and present danger
    	-speech inherently of low value (false stmts)

    	these kind of speech can be subjected to regs that do not need to survive SS

    	instead, they have to pass [the brandenburg test]

    		[
    		-speech to incite
    		-likely to incite
    		]

    3.  GOV CAN REGULATE STUFF THAT DOESN'T HAVE TO DO WITH THE CONTENT OF SPEECH

    	eg noise ordinances
    	time, manner, place
    	if they dont address the content, no need to sweat SS

    	they're not about speech and content

    	gov regs on conduct don't have to pass SS



    	THIS FRAMEWORK reduces a lot of cases to the question:

    		which category do we belong in?




    FALSE STATEMENTS LAST TIME

    SYMBOLIC CONDUCT THIS TIME

    	how do we know if symbolic action counts as speech?





    US v OBRIEN

    	some kids burn their draft cards

    	the court does not apply SS,

    		despite the kid asserting that he was doing first amendment stuff

    	they ask for an important or substantial gov interest

    		this is like IR

    	4 part obrien test:

    		-within gov's constitutional power
    		-important gov interest
    		-interest is unrelated to supression of free speech
    		-least restricive method (lowest possible impact on 1A rights)

    		the purpose of the test is to make sure the gov is regulating the nonspeech element

    		if the gov was regulating the speech element, SS applies

    			if gov fails the obrien test, then we default to SS

    	key issue of this case:

    		UNITY OF SPEECH AND ACTION

    		the same action can have speech elements and nonspeech elements

    		but the court can't just treat everything with speech elements as speech

    			that would draw in a shitload of other acts

    			speech through conduct could be almost anything

    				even robbing could be a political expression against tax code
    				urination on the courthouse steps...
    				anarchy via 1a


    		IF ITS THE NONSPEECH ELEMENT BEING REGULATED, SS DOES NOT APPLY

    			it's not a law on the viewpoint
    			it's a law on the conduct

    		the four part test helps us to figure out whether an act is speech or conduct

    			this test is a bit like the brandenburg test

    				total free speech means chaos
    				total fre symbolic speech means chaos

    			but it's not about what might happen (speech effect on others, who affect order)
    			it's about how much we want to let him get away with (speech effect on order)


    	APPLICATION:

    		-the gov has the constitutional power to reg here
    		-the gov interest in smooth administration is important enough here
    		-the interest is about administration, not speech
    		-the impact is incidental because he could express himself in other ways



    		This is all over the board, SS, IR, RBR

    		admin convenience is a substantial interest for the court here



    NUDE DANCING
    LIVE NUDE GIRLS
    PASTIES AND A G STRING

    	these cases show us how the court works out the fuzziness of the doctrine

    	they also reject the obrien test (it's not deferential enough for them)


    BARNES

    	indiana public indecency law

    	live nude dancing is the conduct

    	eroticism is its message

    	the court applies the obrien test

    		-states have the police power to make this law
    		-the gov has a substantial interest in morality and safety possibly
    		-it's an interest unrelated to the interest in suppressing free speech
    			it's a general law, applicable to speech and nonspeech contexts
    		-there's only an incidental effect because there's still plenty of erotic stuff
    			pasites and a g string only minimally impact the message
    			the message can still be communicated even if nude dancing is shutdown

    		the law satisfies obrien, debate over

    	WHITE: this is a general law, sure, but its only being applied to nude dancing

    		the gov hates this speech and its content

    		he'd apply SS

    	SOUTER: maybe nudity here produces secondary problems that aren't about speech

    		SECONDARY EFFECTS can give a the gov grounds to reg

    	SCALIA: it's a general law, regulates conduct not speech



    CITY OF ERIE v PAP'S AM

    	city makes a ban on live nude dancing
    	it's a targeted law, not a general ban on nudity

    	they apply obrien test

    		-police power
    		-substantial interest
    			in safety RE: secondary effects
    			they also see a general purpose
    			which allows them to fare better on the next prong
    		-the interest is unrelated
    		-incidental effect bc pasties and g string OK

    	SCALIA: its a conduct law, no Q of FR, no SS, only RBR



CON LAW DAY 24:

    REVIEW:

        we did three kinds of free speech analysis

            -dangerous speech
            -false speech
            -symbolic speech

        Symbolic Speech

            key case: OBRIEN

                four part test

                    if fails, apply SS
                        bc they're targeting speech
                    if passes, gov has more wiggle room
                        bc they're targeting action

                protected all symbolic speech causes anarchy

                4 factors of obrien test:

                    -within gov's constitutional power?
                    -furthers an important or substantial interest? (like IR)
                    -UNRELATED TO THE SUPPRESSION OF SPEECH?
                    -incidental restriction/ narrowest tailoring?

                    it's a deferential test, easy for gov to satisfy

                    smooth administration (normally only good for RBR) flies here

                how good is the court at applying the test?

                    when will they recognize targeting of speech?
                    how easily can they determine if the state's interest is unrelated?

                LIVE NUDE DANCING can be prohibited

                    because its a de minimis impact on speech

                SCALIA thinks it's all conduct, no speech

                    he thinks the obrien test is TOO difficult

                    he'd only apply RBR

                WHITE thinks it's all speech

                    the gov wants to shut down the erotic message

                SOUTER thinks the gov's interest is in secondary crime prevention

            CITY OF ERIE v PAPS AM

                the city advances the souter secondary interest

                but the court says, nah, you don't mean that

                they find a workable interest for the gov

                they see a general interest

                they spin the situation to satisfy the obrien test


    TODAY:

        WE TACKLE FREEDOM OF RELIGION AND ANTIESTABLISHMENT

        ORIGINALISM is a big approach in this context

            what were the framers really thinking?

        TEXTUALISM is big too

            what to the precise words do to impact it all?



        WE DO FIVE BROAD ISSUES INSTEAD


            1- what is the SCOPE of the establishment clause?

                was it designed to prevent the gov from preferring one over another?

                    this would allow the gov to support religion

                or was it made to prevent the gov from favoring religion over non-religion?

                    this is a vision of strict separation and neutrality

            2- what can the first amendment guarantees of free exercise and est mean as our society changes?

                we have more divsersity now than at the founding
                we have a MUCH larger gov, regulates more of our lives

                    blaisdell: the gov must reg to allow us our liberties
                    this would mean the est clause shrinks

            3- what is the problem the est clause is trying to address?

                historically there was tax and attendance coercion
                    a narrow view of est clause says this only is prohibited
                    a broader view is that the clause prevents any gov endorsement of religion

            4- who is protected by the establishment clause?

                does it protect the gov from religion?

                    protects our political disputes from becoming theological disputes, which would make compromise harder

                does it protect religion from gov?

                    religious groups would start to care about gov
                    theyd become concerned with the affairs of the world

            5- what is the meaning of "religion" in the first amendment?

                what counts?  should anything and everything count?
                how does gov decide what religion is?
                they can't just let us each define it for ourselves
                    it's the free speech anarchy problem
                    "i wasnt speeding i was praying"


            NOT ALL OF THESE COME UP IN EVERY CASE

                but they all flow along the broad/narrow divide

                guarantee of free exercise suggests broad support of rel
                anti est clause suggests a limit on that

        EVERSON v BOARD OF EDUCATION

            FACTS: gov subsidizes catholic private schools

            [traditionally the sponsored one religion and blocked others]
            [the colonies developed the same old problems]
            [VA blocks a law to support a state church]

            Jefferson:

                "true religion did not need the support of law"
                "God hath created the mind free"

                it's a religious argument for religious tolerance

                these arguments fall on the ears of their contemporaries well

                        it lets strong religion permeate society

            What does the est clause mean?

                the gov cannot:

                    set up a church
                    force attendance
                    forbid attendance
                    use tax money to support a church
                    participate in any religious group

                there's a wall of separation between religion and fed

                    so we can have stronger religion

            NEW JERSEY WAS ALLOWED TO USE TAXPAYER MONEY TO SUBSIDIZE RELIGION

                how can we reconcile that?

                there's an AMENITIES ARGUMENT:

                    you can't take an amenity away from a religious group
                    est clause is powerful until it hits free exercise

                    you can't separate the practice of religion from to provision of gov services

                        "everyone gets this except you"
                        "we can't use taxpayer money to put out the fire in a church" sounds too crazy to the court

                        you can't stop building a sidewalk in front of a church

                    this frees up money for the church to evangelize, though

                        this logic is not accepted here

                    the separation is to allow true religion to flourish

                        est and free ex clause both point to the goal of promotion of religion in the mind of the court

        LEE v WEISMAN

            FACTS: school had a rabbi give a nonsectarian prayer at graduation

                a rabbi gives a prayer
                but the ceremony was effectively mandatory
                it was

            the student sues becauase the prayer is a violation of the establishment clause

                [there's gonna be two different tests for EST and FE]

            THE GOV ACTED. set up by school.

                managed by the school and permitted by the principle

            THE GOV HERE TRIES TO ADVANCE RELIGION GENERALLY

                just because theyre not advancing one single religion, theyre not off the hook

                the oppressors claim it's all just american, no big deal

                SCALIA: we say this stuff all the time without thinking of it as religious

                the court doesnt buy the bullshit

                it's a civic religion that the gov is trying to endorse

                    just because it's broadly acceptable to religions across a spectrum doesnt mean that youre not trying to create a religion

                    the fact it doesnt map to any one religion doesnt excuse your shit

            HAS THE GOV ESTABLISHED A RELIGION?

                Kennedy IDs objections and handles them

                O: curriculum involves distasteful ideas often.  this prayer is no big deal in comparison.

                    K: doesn't hold water.  there's a difference between freedom of speech in the classroom and freedom of religion here.

                        the goal of free speech is to find truth the gov can act on

                        the goal of free religion is not to impact gov action

                O: this is not establishment bc no coercion. you don't have to go, you don't have to pray.

                    K: there is coercion

                        graduation is important, norms make it compulsory even in absence of an official rule

                        there's no viable way to not participate

                        the coercion is there

                            coercion can be social, psychological

                    K: there's no such thing as non-participation

                O: the reason for the prayer is because graduation is so important. we render it more solemn.  it dignifies the event.

                    K: it forgets about the dissenters.

                        you can't take the perspective of the gov or an adherent.

                        why not just tell the dissenters to sit?  because then the individual dissenter must protect his own right.

                            it'd be like saying "gov can censor, you just have to find a way to avoid it" != free speech protection

            SCALIA: writes dissents for law students.

                he sees consequences to nonsectarian prayer

                but theyre different from the madison jefferson concerns

                nonsectarian prayer is a unifying mechanism for different religions

                he sees minimal inconvenience for the dissenters

                and

                major benefits to the sheep

                it wouldnt have the same effect at home

                it's important that it's nonsectarian and public

                he dissents but channels the logic of the everson opinion


CON LAW DAY 25

	REVIEW SESSIONS: 12/15 - 12/17  T,W,Th 1-3 Rm 434

	REVIEW:

		five kinds of issues:

			-what is the scope of establishment clause?
				to prohibit favoring one religion
				to prohibit favoring religion

			-what of the changes since the founding?
				growth in diversity in US religions
				extension of the new deal blaisdell gov

			-what is the relationship to coercion?
				historically this was a big concern
				is there a broader definition now
				is mere endorsement violative
				what is the breadth of the definition of coercion

			-what is the est clause there to do?
				is it pitted against the free exercise clause
				is it there to protect religion from gov
				maybe they both trend toward allowing religion to thrive

			-what is the meaning of religion in the first amendment?
				can it be totally self defined (anarchy!)
				can the court come up with a definition
					is a gov definition an est clause problem
		EVERSON:

			dicta suggests a total wall between church and state
			holding is contrary to that though
				church subsidy is upheld

			how to reconcile?

				the idea is that the establishment clause serves true religion
				freely given conviction is the hallmark of true religion

				to fail to pay for transportation would be the equivalent

					of denying sidewalks, fire fighting, etc to church
					it would make the state the adversary of religion

				it's about making sure the gov can't intrude

				the gov can fund religion, so long as it does so neutrally

		LEE v WEISMAN:

			school gives a prayer at graduation

			violates est clause

				bc its coercive
				not de jure, but de facto

					adolescents feel those social pressures
					theyll feel compelled to at least act like theyre playing

				coercion is contextual under this version of the est clause

			theres a difference between religion and speech

				you should have to hear things you don't want to

					the clash of ideas produces stability, truth, self gov

				religion is different

					the state is not the target of persuasion in religious debate

					we don't want gov to adopt religion
					we want religion to be personal

					even if we all agreed, we don't want the gov in the religion biz

			There's a coherent argument here, but no tidy doctrine

				we don't know quite what to do with the next case

		The Lemon test is the main doctrinal test

			but the court is ambivalent about the test though

			it's present, but the court uses and abuses it

				keeps it close, tosses it aside

			does it violate est clause?

			THREE COMPONENTS:

				-does the gov have a secular purpose?
				-what is the primary effect?
					is it to enhance or protect a religion?
				-does the gov action promote excessive administrative entanglement with religion?

			Everson:

				-secular purpose is to promote education
				-primary effect is to provide universal general services
				-admin entanglement minimal no prob

			Lee v Weisman:

				-secular purposeis to solemnize
				-primary effect is to advance religion (PROBLEMATIC)
				-minimal entanglement no prob


	TODAY:

		Lynch v Donnelly

			Pawtucket RI displays holiday decorations including a nativity scene

			Court breaks out Lemon test

				-secular purpose is to celebrate the season
				-court sees no effect of advancing religion
					(maybe an incidental indirect effect of advancing rel)
					they know this because it's analogous to museum displays
				-entanglement is no prob. it's cheap and easy to store.
					no religious involvement in the gov's dealings

			OCONNOR is a little unhappy with all this

				uncertainty about whether it's really advancing religion or not

				she develops the ENDORSEMENT TEST

				two ways for violations of est clause to happen

					entanglement and endorsement

						entanglement compromises religious independance

						endorsement is like a combo of lemon purp and effect

							endorsement can include coercion
							but it doesnt have to in order to violate

					they both have in common that they effect a person's standing in the political community

						entanglement ties the two up
						endorsement makes insiders and outsiders

					if some gov action causes your religion to become meaningful in the political community, it violates the est clause

				she looks at purpose and effect too

					she just frames it in a way that she thinks is more useful doctrinally

				she claims they don't intend to endorse christianity

					they just want to celebrate the holiday

				she claims the action doesn't have the effect of endorsing religion

					the intended message is not endorsement
					the received message is not endorsement

				she COMPARES TO MONEY not museums

					money uses 'in god we trust' but it's merely solemnizing and giving a sense of a positive future

					no endorsement of deistic religions over nondeistic
					no endorsement of religion over nonreligion

				THIS IS A LOT LIKE THE MAJORITY SO FAR

					celebrate season
					depict "historical" origins of holiday

					it's not religious just like in god we trust

					but also

				it caused NO POLITICAL DIVISIVENESS

					it met no opposition

						this is evidence that the message received was nonreligious

			BRENNAN

				rejects all this

					he says its demeaning to christians to say it carries no religious weight

					he shows a lack of actual historical support for public celebration of christmas

					he thinks there can't be a secular purpose to displaying an inherently religious symbol

					he thinks there can be no effect but advancement of religion in displaying an inherently religious symbol

				He's willing to put up with a lot of bullshit, to be sure

					but he's just not convinced in this case


		MUELLER V ALLEN

			income tax incentive for sending kids to private [religious] shcools

				we have in paractice an advantage only available to parents who send their kids to religious schools

			the court applies the lemon test and finds no problem

				-ct: the secular purpose is to broadly advance education
				-ct: the effect is to advance education but not religion
				-ct: no excessive entanglement

			that its in fact a subsidy to religious schools doesn't matter to the court

				ct: the money doesn't really go all the way to the school
					the gov subsidy is for parents.  gov responsibility ends there
					the parents's choice launders the money constitutionally

				they decline to look to empirical evidence that the gov is subsidizing the church

				they spin private education as releiving the burden on public schools

				there's no entanglement bc this is just any old deduction

					no need for entanglement with religious schools

			THE COURT ONLY CARES ABOUT FORMAL EQUALITY

				not about following through to see effects

				think strader:

					EP gives you formal access, but no guarantee of a mixed jury

				think washington and mcklesky:

					racially discriminatory results are not enough
					effects alone arent enough

			The Lemon test claims to care about effects alone

				but they dont live up to that

			Ostensibly, if you fail any prong you violate the est clause

				mere effect of advancing religion violates, supposedly

			The court, to make up for it, decides how far to follow the effects

				the buck stops with the parents for the ct's analysis


		ZELMAN V SIMMONS-HARRIS

			voucher programs subsidize private schools

			not a tax deduction, but money to pay tuition

				if public school, the school gets bonus funding
				if private school, the church gets the funding

				very direct

			LEMON TEST:

				-secular purpose?
				-primary effect of advancing religion?
				-excessive entanglement?

				-there is a secular purpose of educating poor children

				-the primary effect is not to advance religion, but rather to advance education

					not all the money goes to religious schools

						maj: channels everson
						souter: any amount to church is a problem

					again, the parents's choice launders the tax money

						souter: there is no real choice here

							religious schools are really the only choice

							you can't innoculate the state with the parents choice argument if the parent's don't have a real choice

							no firewall unless there's a meaningful choice

						maj:  there is a real choice at play

							there are other options
							there's disincentives to send kids to religious schools

								magnet schools get more money

						THIS CASE:

							similar to mueller
								applies lemon test
								state no helping religion, helping families

							different to mueller
								ct focuses more on realness of choice
								more direct subsidy to church

							there's no primary effect as long as parents choose

					starting in lynch v donnelly, court looks to

						CONTEXT
						HISTORY
						INTERMEDIARY CHOICE

						in each case, gov supports religion
						but not in a way they find violative of the est clause

					ct's weird about lemon.  these cases are fact-intensive


		TOWN OF GREECE v GALLOWAY

			town starts legislative sessions with prayer
			ministers give sectarian invocations

			KENNEDY:

				writes for maj

				talks about the long history of legislative prayer

					first congress opened with prayer
					old as our gov itself

					he claims history doesnt decide it, but provides context

					tips in favor of constitutionality

				est clause limits on the kinds of prayers:

					they could rotate through religions
					a few sectarian prayers would be fine too
					one person's objection alone is not enough
						no heckler's veto
					reasonable observer test
						comes from OCONNOR
						if a very well informed person heard the prayer and saw it as consistent with the history, no prob
						as long as it's made to give a sense of collective confidence, it's fine

				gov can't censor or inspect the prayers beforehand

					that's an example of entanglement
					happens to violate the leg of lemon test

				THE LEMON TEST IS NOT EXPLICITLY USED

					but we can map the case to it nonetheless

			KAGAN:

				writes for dissenters
				she sees est clause problem

				she imagines a muslim woman observer instead

					that observer would feel excluded from the political community because of her religious belief

					she'd feel excluded from the [zoning] discussion

					she'd be an outsider or she's forced to pray as a christian

				Kagan says we pick our imaginary observer from the perspective of a religiously pluralistic society

					if the dissenting minority feels like there's no endorsement, then there's no endorsement
